<div class="postright">
<h3>TUTORIAL: Simple cashe control settings</h3>
<div class="postmsg">
<p><strong>TUTORIAL:</strong> Simple cache-control.</p><p>These simple and easy tricks prevents cache cluttering a bit and decreases memory cache so you will have more free memory at your disposal. I am using older machines without a ton of memory so I will share these settings with you.</p><p><span class="bbu">Open SYNAPTIC package manager</span> and click on &quot;settings &gt; preferences &gt; files&quot;.</p><p>* <strong>Temporary files:</strong> select &quot;Delete packages after installation&quot;. Speaks for itself what it does, right? Saves some disk space and will keep things neat and organized.</p><p>* <strong>History files</strong>: Select &quot;Delete History files older then&quot; &gt; set preferred period in days files will be kept. Don&#039;t choose 0. 3 days is fine and you will be able to troubleshoot package problems IF they may occur for whatever reason.</p><p><strong><span class="bbu">STEP 2</span></strong></p><p><strong>Open DCONFEDITOR:</strong> org &gt; gnome &gt; desktop &gt; thumbnail-cache</p><p>*<span class="bbu">Double-click maximum-age</span> and set value to 5 (days). Now in stead of 180 days the system will keep thumbnails only for 5 days. See that switch for &#039;keep default value? Click it to turn it off in order to set your value. When done hit the save icon in de lower right corner of the window.</p><p>*<span class="bbu">Double click maximum-size</span> and set value to 64. Now the size of your thumbnails are drastically smaller. Save and close dconfeditor.</p><p>That&#039;s it. Set it and forget it. Now this is very basic of course and it will not prevent all cluttering but this is a step into the right direction.<br/>These settings will not influence the performance of your system in a negative way whatsoever. Been using these settings for 3 years now without any problems.</p><p>Enjoy! M.B.</p>
</div>
<div class="postsignature postmsg"><hr/><p>Encourage and teach others to be better at Linux stuff. Don&#039;t talk &#039;em down but help them. We are all in the same boat.</p></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
